{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475077"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:28:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:28:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12522"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12522"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.67,0.05,0.04,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5023"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112501"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5023"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94535"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3774"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10997"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8342"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36033"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46195"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112501"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents with a three-month history of fatigue and difficulty keeping up with friends during sports. He complains of tiredness and shortness of breath during physical activity. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His parents are both of Mediterranean descent, and he eats a well-balanced diet. On examination, he appears pale. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 104/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. His full blood count shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 73 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERed cell count 5.8 x 10\u003Csup\u003E12\u003C/sup\u003E/L (3.8-4.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume 58 fL (77-95)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 7.68 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.5-13.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 179 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA blood smear reveals hypochromic, microcytic red cells with numerous target cells and occasional nucleated red blood cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to provide the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bone marrow biopsy","Haemoglobin electrophoresis","Direct antiglobulin test","Reticulocyte count","Serum ferritin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with microcytic anaemia, a well-balanced diet, and a family background from the Mediterranean region, all of which are highly suggestive of thalassaemia. The blood smear findings of hypochromic, microcytic red cells with target cells and nucleated red blood cells further support this diagnosis. Notably, the red cell count is elevated despite the low haemoglobin, which is characteristic of thalassaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is the key investigation, as it separates and quantifies different haemoglobin types, allowing for the diagnosis and classification of thalassaemia and other haemoglobinopathies. In beta thalassaemia, for example, there is an increase in haemoglobin F and/or haemoglobin A2, which is diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone marrow biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for suspected bone marrow failure syndromes, leukaemia, or unexplained cytopenias. It is invasive and not required for the diagnosis of thalassaemia, which can be made non-invasively with haemoglobin studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect antiglobulin test\u003C/strong\u003E (direct Coombs test) detects antibodies or complement on red blood cells and is used to diagnose autoimmune haemolytic anaemia. There is no evidence of haemolysis or immune-mediated red cell destruction in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReticulocyte count\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated in thalassaemia due to increased red cell turnover, but it is not diagnostic and cannot distinguish between causes of microcytic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum ferritin\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for assessing iron stores and diagnosing iron deficiency anaemia, which is an important cause of microcytic anaemia to consider. However, this child has a normal diet and no risk factors for iron deficiency, and the clinical context with elevated red cell count is more consistent with haemoglobinopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThalassaemia is an inherited disorder of haemoglobin synthesis, most common in people of Mediterranean, Middle Eastern, South Asian, and African ancestry. Aside from iron deficiency, it is an important cause of microcytic anaemia to consider. The evaluation for thalassaemia includes full blood count, blood smear, haemoglobin electrophoresis, high-pressure liquid chromatography, and molecular testing in some cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Common causes of microcytic anaemia in children are iron deficiency and haemoglobinopathies/thalassaemias.","Haemoglobin electrophoresis is an important investigation for diagnosing thalassaemia and other haemoglobinopathies.","In thalassaemia, the red cell count is often relatively preserved despite low haemoglobin, unlike in iron deficiency anaemia."],"references":["Bajwa H, Basit H. Thalassemia. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94535"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12522"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94535"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T08:03:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T08:06:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5023"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112501"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda